Title: How to catch multiple exceptions in one line? (in the catch block).
Body: <p>I know that I can do:</p>
<pre><code>try {
    // do something that may fail
} catch (Exception $e) {
    // do this if ANYTHING goes wrong
}
</code></pre>
<p>I can also do this:</p>
<pre><code>try {
    // do something that may fail
} catch (IDontLikeYouException $e) {
    // say please
} catch (YouAreTooShortException $e) {
    // stand on a ladder
}
</code></pre>
<p>But if I want to do the same thing inside two different exceptions, the best I can think of right now is to do this:</p>
<pre><code>try {
    // do something that may fail
} catch (IDontLikeYouException $e) {
    // say please
} catch (YouAreBeingMeanException $e) {
    // say please
}
</code></pre>
<p>Is there any way that I can do something like this (since the action to take in both exceptions is to <code>say please</code>):</p>
<pre><code>try {
    // do something that may fail
} catch (IDontLikeYouException | YouAreBeingMeanException $e) {
    // say please
}
</code></pre>
<p>So, my effort to catch the two distinct exceptions doesn't exactly come through.</p>
<p>Is there a way to do this?</p>

Title: How do I check if an array includes a value in PHP?
Body: <p>What is the most concise and efficient way to find out if a PHP array contains a value?</p>
<p>This is the only way I know to do it:</p>
<pre><code>function contains($a, $obj) {
    for ($i = 0; $i &lt; count($a); $i++) {
        if ($a[$i] === $obj) {
