Title: What does onDelete do in Laravel migrations?
Body: <p>I'm quite familiar with Laravel, but I recently noticed there exists an <code>onDelete('cascade')</code> option with foreign keys in migrations. I have searched for the documentation for the same, but I couldn't find anything more than:</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Changed in Laravel 5.8:</strong></p>
<p><code>onDelete</code> can now be used fluently when defining foreign keys. It will be a required argument in future versions.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><a href="https://laravel.com/docs/migrations#foreign-key-constraints" rel="noreferrer">An example case of usage is</a>:</p>
<pre><code>use Illuminate\Database\Migrations\Migration;
use Illuminate\Database\Schema\Blueprint;
use Illuminate\Support\Facades\Schema;

class CreateCarsTable extends Migration
{
    public function up()
    {
        Schema::create('cars', function (Blueprint $table) {
            $table->id();
            $table->foreignId('manufacturer_id')
                  ->constrained('manufacturers')
                  ->onDelete('cascade');
            // ...
        });
    }
}
</code></pre>
<p>What does <code>onDelete</code> do? (<em>I guess the actions to be done if the related model is deleted</em>.)</p>
<p>What does <code>onDelete('cascade')</code> do? (<em>any hints in documentation</em>)</p>
<p>What other options are available (<em>if my guess is correct</em>)?</p>
<p>Where does the documentation for this reside?</p>

